full_text: @EmAsInMoney @JazdzewskiTara I use general reader feedback for market advice more than creative advice. Readers dictate the market. The market dictates publishing. Publishing dictates book deals. Asking readers in polls what kind of stories they wish were being told is a great way to size up your horizon.

b"@JosephJMiccolis Disagree.

full_text:
Lynn's dad sat with her in the park, flipping pages in an animal picture book.

"What's the dog say?"

Lynn made a bark.

"What's the horse say?"

Lynn made a trumpet sound.

"No, #horses don't make trumpet sounds."

Pointing to the the sky, she said,

"Those four do."
#vss365

full_text(utf-8): b"@Homegrowngirl2 @abbythetweet He then storms off shouting that she missed her chance to be with a true classy man. Moments later he remembers that she'd picked him up in her car. full_text:
@inferno4dante My cousin Greg dropped a metal He-Man lunchbox over our balcony when we were kids and it busted the windshield of a parked car.

We were sort of freaking out and I then I decided to throw the thermos at his car too because I thought it would look less suspicious for some reason.

full_text:
I stand among the mourners. By our quant traditions a #tribute is given that reflects the departed's contributions in life.

When the baker died we gave apples. The farmer we gave corn.

I pick up the pliers and slowly open my mouth. 

Why did it have to be our dentist.
#vss365

full_text:
New folks at the beach. Said they come here to feed the birds. We laugh. Hey did they mess with my water bottle? The cap was loose. Shit I can't move. I'm paralyzed. I hear them laughing. A #seagull lands on my stomach. More follow. I scream until they eat my throat.
#vss365

#vss365

full_text:

@BarrySBrunswick @DzintraSullivan @Ned_the_zombie @JaysQuill @Chrissy_Clarke @woodcowbooks @KeysDorian @SJTurner_Author @inkedingray @BellaRayne10 @LawrenceWriting @CRTaylorwrites @FaerieRealms @TTBanks5 @TJPayne3333 @joanne_paulson @Johnldeboer @DisparoJack @JonathanMette @bonblossman @disneymom1126 @Ltward2 @HLNida2 @MarkSagarin @ctamarketing @ZenaAZellers @xxxBJFrazier @nikki_twisted @Wordsmith66 @d_ast777 @JaysinYerxa @DebbieGrimshaw2 @HABlackwood7 @ClaireLLLW81 @lyv0n @Kungfuponder It's because we're conditioned from children to be subject matter experts instead of jacks of all trades.

Our educations are more intensive than comprehensive. Even in zombie movies you never see people repairing the power plants or sewer pumps.

full_text:
@ItsNicoleCarman Please believe me when I say I'm not trying to be a contrarian here. This is how so many big regret stories begin. 

Why not split the difference. Move closer to the beach. Walkable distance. Test it out first. If you still love it, now you'll have experience to help you decide.

full_text:
@Insomniak_Fears Not trying to sound contrary, I'm simply curious, but how does one categorize themselves as having a pure heart? 

The phrase is more or less an idealized platitude on its own. What are the attributes of being pure hearted?
full_text(utf-8): b"@Insomniak_Fears Not trying to sound contrary, I'm simply curious, but how does one categorize themselves as having a pure heart? \n\nThe phrase is more or less an idealized platitude on its own. What are the attributes of being pure hearted?"

b"@rhymescribe This is a paradox so I can't give a yes or no. 

If I restarted my life with no awareness that it restarted I wouldn't be able to change anything because I'd have no comparable memories.

If I had full awareness then it's already different thus invalidating the option of choice."

full_text:
@ItsNicoleCarman Ultimately my advice is follow your heart but let your brain scout ahead first. A beloved retreat ceases being a retreat when you move it. 

The charm of the place can lose its shine when applied full time. Like a day at the pool. It's fun up until you're ready to go home.

@TheKateDylan I totally respect all of that. As long as the advice comes from positive intent it's good advice.

My thoughts on this are far more directed to the over abundance of "gatekeepers" within our craft. The "reader" trope is what's fetishized.

Rambo mops floor with killer. She rocks him back to the fucking Stone Age. Killer unconscious on ground. Rambo gets in car and leaves. Credits roll. Cue part 2.
full_text(utf-8): b"@TraCee_tr Okay - I'll raise. Keys to my Maybach. (The one in my mind anyway)\n\nRambo mops floor with killer. She rocks him back to the fucking Stone Age. Killer unconscious on ground. Rambo gets in car and leaves. Credits roll. Cue part 2."

full_text:
@TheKateDylan My issue isn't with the advice itself. It's good advice. 

It's also disengaging advice. To fetishize reading isn't to recommend it. It ignores the fact that writing is patently different than reading. It condenses the nuanced nature of art into an overly simplistic buzzword.
full_text(utf-8): b"@TheKateDylan My issue isn't with the advice itself. It's good advice. \n\nIt's also disengaging advice. To fetishize reading isn't to recommend it. It ignores the fact that writing is patently different than reading. It condenses the nuanced nature of art into an overly simplistic buzzword."

full_text:
@TraCee_tr I'll see that and raise: Friend who is safely at home gets frantic call. Caller gives location and clearly is in immediate danger. Call cuts out.

Does friend call cops? No. Friend goes alone. Announces arrival with honking of horn and shouting.
full_text(utf-8): b"@TraCee_tr I'll see that and raise: Friend who is safely at home gets frantic call. Caller gives location and clearly is in immediate danger. Call cuts out.\n\nDoes friend call cops? No. Friend goes alone. Announces arrival with honking of horn and shouting."

full_text:
@TraCee_tr Quadruple points - the solo cop arrives and gets killed in two seconds and no more cops ever come to see what happened.

"He was dispatched hours ago to investigate a potential murder but I guess he quit the force on the way there. He can keep the damn squad car."
full_text(utf-8): b'@TraCee_tr Quadruple points - the solo cop arrives and gets killed in two seconds and no more cops ever come to see what happened.\n\n"He was dispatched hours ago to investigate a potential murder but I guess he quit the force on the way there. He can keep the damn squad car."'

b'@TheKateDylan I respectfully disagree. Reading is valuable - no doubt. But reading simply shows the finished product. 

Looking at a cake doesn't tell me how it was made.

Telling people to just read isn't useful advice for writing. Unless the book is "Writing for Beginners."'
